90","about 1162":"about 1162","1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1224":"1224","1144":"1144","Abt 1215":"about 1215","about 1236":"about 1236","1273":"1273","1162":"1162","1182":"1182","Abt 1190":"about 1190","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Longford, Derbyshire, England":"Longford, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Longford, Wiltshire, England":"Longford, Wiltshire, England","Longford Castle, Bodenham, Salisbury, Wiltshire, England":"Bodenham, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Waleran","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Walburn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Walburn","meanings":["English (Durham and North Yorkshire): habitational name from Walburn in Downholme (North Yorkshire). The placename probably derives from Old English <i>wala</i>, genitive plural of <i>walh</i> ‘foreigner, Briton, serf’, + <i>burna</i> ‘spring, stream’. Alternatively, the name may derive from the Old French personal name <i>Walebron</i>, perhaps itself from ancient Germanic <i>Waldbrand</i> (<i>wald</i> ‘power, rule’ + <i>brand</i> ‘sword’)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":53,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":62,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William de Waleran was born about 1162, in Longford, Wiltshire, England as the son of Baroness Isabel of Whatton. He married Isabel Berkeley in 1182, in Bodenham, Wiltshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died about 1236, in his hometown, at the age of 76."},"et":{"about 1162–about 1236":"umbes 1162–umbes 1236","1162–1236":"1162–1236","1162–1215":"1162–1215","1190–1273":"1190–1273","–Female":"Surnud","1144–Female":"1144–Surnud","1190":"1190","about 1162":"umbes 1162","1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1224":"1224","1144":"1144","Abt 1215":"umbes 1215","about 1236":"umbes 1236","1273":"1273","1162":"1162","1182":"1182","Abt 1190":"umbes 1190","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Longford, Derbyshire, England":"Longford, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Longford, Wiltshire, England":"Longford, Wiltshire, England","Longford Castle, Bodenham, Salisbury, Wiltshire, England":"Bodenham, Wiltshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1162–about 1236":"noin 116